<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 478px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Join Order Modification</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p>This technique involves adjusting the default join order of modeled elements to align with the geometry requirement of rules of measurement.&nbsp;</p>
<p>This adjustment ensures that the connections between elements follow the prescribed guidelines, as illustrated in Figure 01.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Although authoring BIM tools offer options for altering join orders, this process often requires manual intervention.&nbsp;</p>
<p>External plugins can streamline the process by automating join order adjustments based on hierarchical rules among elements.</p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;<img src="https://private.lodplanner.com/projects/53934/plan-content/1709310179001_2ffe5b41-e94d-4d72-9784-1df30a295ea9.png?Expires=1768815902&amp;Signature=krC097zNVeQud-NXLdNzLdy98oee-V8AcmKAzJ9kI55aE5N5W-b2xESQe8t~ojcBBfy8plJ-JFBi2LVdXON~OcHXzd21YJRPCE7YQ6gSShEipoQLnRNivdabiBCF7xR04zLOZAYElEeOeAR8M47hc2iCVFEDlW~aTVpYEsH~~ovtzJx7ywziVKIwsdNqP8zGWfyFFc8BLtOxW9oToz9ZEZg7uBKZSeZIOV~CRGYLafqhEnRd2gVk-V2HpsdBijxzSEe~TZlL32Ma3ZXjRfJueiI3i8Umhpoyeto5SGsAgtTTPfXe07560WFqU8J5oIk9lxiRlqSUUvA5~nL-Dyrl9Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" style="width: 755px;" class="fr-fic fr-dib"></strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Figure 01 - Example of modified join order of structural elements, to comply with an example of Rule of Measurement.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">While following this path, it is crucial to conduct thorough quality checks on the model to verify the accuracy of join orders, particularly if the model will be used as a reference for early-stage rebar estimates.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Additionally, incorporating the material specifications of structural elements into the model is equally important.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">This step can influence join orders and impact the corresponding concrete volume calculations.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">The model modification approach not only provides the flexibility to adapt the concrete model for early-stage rebar estimates but also remains well-suited for companies to retain the efficiency of their default modeling processes while ensuring quantities align with specific measurement standards.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>